# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: analog-to-digital-conversion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In electronics, an **analog-to-digital converter** (**ADC**, **A/D**, or **A-to-D**) is a system that converts an analog signal, such as from fingers touching a touchscreen, sound entering a microphone, or light entering a digital camera, into a digital signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC may also provide an isolated measurement, such as an electronic device that converts an analog input voltage or current to a digital number representing the magnitude of the voltage or current.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Typically, the digital output is a two's complement binary number that is proportional to the input, but there are other possibilities.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Due to the complexity and the need for precisely matched components, all but the most specialized ADCs are implemented as integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] These typically take the form of metal–oxide–semiconductor (MOS) mixed-signal integrated circuit chips that integrate both analog and digital circuits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A digital-to-analog converter (DAC) performs the reverse function; it converts a digital signal into an analog signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC converts a continuous-time and continuous-amplitude analog signal to a discrete-time and discrete-amplitude digital signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The conversion involves quantization of the input, so it necessarily introduces a small amount of quantization error.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Furthermore, instead of continuously performing the conversion, an ADC does the conversion periodically, sampling the input, and limiting the allowable bandwidth of the input signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The performance of an ADC is primarily characterized by its bandwidth, dynamic range and signal-to-noise and distortion ratio (SNDR).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The bandwidth of an ADC is set largely by its sampling rate.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The SNDR is influenced by many factors, including the resolution, noise floor, linearity and accuracy (how well the quantization levels match the true analog signal).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Aliasing and jitter will degrade these specifications.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The SNDR of an ADC is often summarized in terms of its effective number of bits (ENOB), the number of bits of each measure it returns that are, on average, not noise.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] An ideal ADC has an ENOB equal to its resolution.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] If an ADC operates at a sampling rate greater than twice the bandwidth of the signal, then per the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem, near-perfect reconstruction is possible.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The presence of quantization error limits the SNDR of even an ideal ADC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] When the SNDR of the ADC exceeds that of the input signal, the effects of quantization error may be neglected, resulting in an essentially perfect digital representation of the bandlimited analog input signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution of the converter indicates the number of different, i.e., discrete, values it can produce over the allowed range of analog input values.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Thus, a particular resolution determines the magnitude of the quantization error and therefore determines the maximum possible signal-to-noise ratio for an ideal ADC without the use of oversampling.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The input samples are usually stored electronically in binary form within the ADC, so the resolution is usually expressed in bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Resolution can also be defined electrically, and expressed in volts.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The change in voltage required to guarantee a change in the output code level is called the least significant bit (LSB) voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution *Q* of the ADC is equal to the LSB voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] where *M* is the ADC's resolution in bits and *E*FSR is the full-scale voltage range (also called 'span').
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] where *V*RefHi and *V*RefLow are the upper and lower extremes, respectively, of the voltages that can be coded.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] where *M* is the ADC's resolution in bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] That is, one voltage interval is assigned in between two consecutive code levels.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In many cases, the useful resolution of a converter is limited by the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) and other errors in the overall system expressed as an ENOB.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error is introduced by the quantization inherent in an ideal ADC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The error is nonlinear and signal-dependent.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] where M is the number of quantization bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, for a 16-bit ADC, the quantization error is 96.3 dB below the maximum level.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error is distributed from DC to the Nyquist frequency.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Consequently, if part of the ADC's bandwidth is not used, as is the case with oversampling, some of the quantization error will occur out-of-band, effectively improving the SQNR for the bandwidth in use.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In an oversampled system, noise shaping can be used to further increase SQNR by forcing more quantization error out of band.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In ADCs, performance can usually be improved using dither.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This is a very small amount of random noise (e.g., white noise), which is added to the input before conversion.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Its effect is to randomize the state of the LSB based on the signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Rather than the signal simply getting cut off altogether at low levels, it extends the effective range of signals that the ADC can convert, at the expense of a slight increase in noise.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Dither can only increase the resolution of a sampler.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] It cannot improve the linearity, and thus, accuracy does not necessarily improve.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization distortion in an audio signal of very low level with respect to the bit depth of the ADC is correlated with the signal and sounds distorted and unpleasant.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] With dithering, the distortion is transformed into noise.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The undistorted signal may be recovered accurately by averaging over time.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Dithering is also used in integrating systems such as electricity meters.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Since the values are added together, the dithering produces results that are more exact than the LSB of the analog-to-digital converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Dither is often applied when quantizing photographic images to a fewer number of bits per pixel—the image becomes noisier but to the eye looks far more realistic than the quantized image, which otherwise becomes banded.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This analogous process may help to visualize the effect of dither on an analog audio signal that is converted to digital.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Quantization error and (assuming the ADC is intended to be linear) non-linearity are intrinsic to any analog-to-digital conversion.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] These errors are measured in a unit called the least significant bit (LSB).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In the above example of an 8-bit ADC, an error of one LSB is 1⁄256 of the full signal range, or about 0.4%.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] All ADCs suffer from nonlinearity errors caused by their physical imperfections, causing their output to deviate from a linear function (or some other function, in the case of a deliberately nonlinear ADC) of their input.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] These errors can sometimes be mitigated by calibration, or prevented by testing.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Important parameters for linearity are integral nonlinearity and differential nonlinearity.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] These nonlinearities introduce distortion that can reduce the signal-to-noise ratio performance of the ADC and thus reduce its effective resolution.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] When digitizing a sine wave $x(t)=A\sin {(2\pi f_{0}t)}$ , the use of a non-ideal sampling clock will result in some uncertainty in when samples are recorded.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Provided that the actual sampling time uncertainty due to clock jitter is $\Delta t$ , the error caused by this phenomenon can be estimated as $E_{ap}\leq |x'(t)\Delta t|\leq 2A\pi f_{0}\Delta t$ .
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This will result in additional recorded noise that will reduce the effective number of bits (ENOB) below that predicted by quantization error alone.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The error is zero for DC, small at low frequencies, but significant with signals of high amplitude and high frequency.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The effect of jitter on performance can be compared to quantization error: $\Delta t<{\frac {1}{2^{q}\pi f_{0}}}$ , where q is the number of ADC bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The resolution of ADCs with a digitization bandwidth between 1 MHz and 1 GHz is limited by jitter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] For lower bandwidth conversions such as when sampling audio signals at 44.1 kHz, clock jitter has a less significant impact on performance.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] An analog signal is continuous in time and it is necessary to convert this to a flow of digital values.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] It is therefore required to define the rate at which new digital values are sampled from the analog signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The rate of new values is called the *sampling rate* or *sampling frequency* of the converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A continuously varying bandlimited signal can be sampled and then the original signal can be reproduced from the discrete-time values by a reconstruction filter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem implies that a faithful reproduction of the original signal is only possible if the sampling rate is higher than twice the highest frequency of the signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Since a practical ADC cannot make an instantaneous conversion, the input value must necessarily be held constant during the time that the converter performs a conversion (called the *conversion time*).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] An input circuit called a sample and hold performs this task—in most cases by using a capacitor to store the analog voltage at the input, and using an electronic switch or gate to disconnect the capacitor from the input.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Many ADC integrated circuits include the sample and hold subsystem internally.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] An ADC works by sampling the value of the input at discrete intervals in time.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Provided that the input is sampled above the Nyquist rate, defined as twice the highest frequency of interest, then all frequencies in the signal can be reconstructed.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] If frequencies above half the Nyquist rate are sampled, they are incorrectly detected as lower frequencies, a process referred to as aliasing.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Aliasing occurs because instantaneously sampling a function at two or fewer times per cycle results in missed cycles, and therefore, the appearance of an incorrectly lower frequency.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, a 2 kHz sine wave being sampled at 1.5 kHz would be reconstructed as a 500 Hz sine wave.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] To avoid aliasing, the input to an ADC must be low-pass filtered to remove frequencies above half the sampling rate.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This filter is called an *anti-aliasing filter*, and is essential for a practical ADC system that is applied to analog signals with higher frequency content.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In applications where protection against aliasing is essential, oversampling may be used to greatly reduce or even eliminate it.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Although aliasing in most systems is unwanted, it can be exploited to provide simultaneous down-mixing of a band-limited high-frequency signal (see undersampling and frequency mixer).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The alias is effectively the lower heterodyne of the signal frequency and sampling frequency.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] For economy, signals are often sampled at the minimum rate required, with the result that the quantization error introduced is white noise spread over the whole passband of the converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Oversampling is typically used in audio frequency ADCs where the required sampling rate (typically 44.1 or 48 kHz) is very low compared to the clock speed of typical transistor circuits (>1 MHz).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In this case, the performance of the ADC can be greatly increased at little or no cost.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Furthermore, as any aliased signals are also typically out of band, aliasing can often be eliminated using very low-cost filters.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The sliding scale method was introduced in 1963 by Cottini, Gatti, and Svelto as a way to reduce differential nonlinearity in analog-to-digital converters used in radiation detection systems.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In those applications, the digital output codes of an ADC are accumulated into histograms representing measured particle energies.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] If some output codes correspond to slightly wider or narrower input voltage ranges than others, the resulting *bins* in the histogram are uneven.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This produces visible structure in what should otherwise be smooth spectra.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The method works by adding a known random analog offset to the input before conversion and subtracting the corresponding digital value afterward.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Although the final numerical result is unchanged, each conversion effectively occurs at a different position along the ADC transfer characteristic.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] When many samples are accumulated, the output codes represent an average over several adjacent code widths, reducing the impact of differential nonlinearity.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] There are several common ways of implementing an electronic ADC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Resistor-capacitor (RC) circuits have a known voltage charging and discharging curve that can be used to solve for an unknown analog value.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The Wilkinson ADC is a type of linear ramp converter, originally described by Denys Wilkinson in 1950.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In this architecture, the input pulse is compared with a linearly voltage ramp generated by charging a capacitor with a constant current source.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A comparator produces a gate signal that remains active until the ramp reaches the amplitude of the input pulse.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The duration of this gate interval is therefore proportional to the input amplitude.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] During this interval, pulses from a constant-frequency clock are counted by a register, and the final count represents the digital output.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Because the ramp can be generated with high precision, the output codes are contiguous and nearly uniform in width, giving the converter good differential linearity.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The conversion time is proportional to the input amplitude and inversely proportional to the clock frequency, so larger signals require longer conversion times.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Wilkinson converters were widely used in multichannel analyzers for nuclear spectroscopy through the 1960s and 1970s due to their linearity and suitability for histogram-based measurements.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] and solving for the unknown resistance or capacitance using those starting and ending datapoints.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This is similar but contrasts with the Wilkinson ADC, which measures an unknown voltage with a known resistance and capacitance, by instead measuring an unknown resistance or capacitance with a known voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] For example, the positive (and/or negative) pulse width from a 555 Timer IC in monostable or astable mode represents the time it takes to charge (and/or discharge) its capacitor from 1⁄3 *V*supply to 2⁄3 *V*supply.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] By sending this pulse into a microcontroller with an accurate clock, the duration of the pulse can be measured and converted using the capacitor charging equation to produce the value of the unknown resistance or capacitance.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Larger resistances and capacitances will take a longer time to measure than smaller ones.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] And the accuracy is limited by the accuracy of the microcontroller clock and the amount of time available to measure the value, which potentially might even change during measurement or be affected by external parasitics.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A flash ADC, also known as a parallel search ADC, employs a bank of voltage comparators sampling the input signal in parallel, each with a different voltage threshold.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit consists of a resistive divider network, a set of voltage comparators and a priority encoder.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Each node of the resistive divider provides a voltage threshold for one comparator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The comparator outputs are applied to a priority encoder, which generates a binary number proportional to the input voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Flash ADCs have a large die size and high power dissipation.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] They are used in a variety of applications, including video, wideband communications, and for digitizing other fast signals.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit has the advantage of high speed as the conversion takes place simultaneously rather than sequentially.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Typical conversion time is 100 ns or less.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Conversion time is limited only by the speed of the comparator and of the priority encoder.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This type of ADC has the disadvantage that for each additional output bit, the number of comparators required almost doubles, and the priority encoder becomes more complex.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A successive-approximation ADC uses a comparator and a binary search to successively narrow a range that contains the input voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] At each successive step, the converter compares the input voltage to the output of an internal digital-to-analog converter (DAC), which initially represents the midpoint of the allowed input voltage range.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] At each step in this process, the approximation is stored in a successive approximation register (SAR) and the output of the digital-to-analog converter is updated for a comparison over a narrower range.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A ramp-compare ADC produces a saw-tooth signal that ramps up or down, then quickly returns to zero.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] When the ramp starts, a timer starts counting.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] When the ramp voltage matches the input, a comparator fires, and the timer's value is recorded.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Timed ramp converters can be implemented economically, however, the ramp time may be sensitive to temperature because the circuit generating the ramp is often a simple analog integrator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A more accurate converter uses a clocked counter driving a DAC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A special advantage of the ramp-compare system is that converting a second signal just requires another comparator and another register to store the timer value.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] To reduce sensitivity to input changes during conversion, a sample and hold can charge a capacitor with the instantaneous input voltage and the converter can time the time required to discharge with a constant current.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] An **integrating ADC** (also **dual-slope** or **multi-slope** ADC) applies the unknown input voltage to the input of an integrator and allows the voltage to ramp for a fixed time period (the run-up period).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Then a known reference voltage of opposite polarity is applied to the integrator and is allowed to ramp until the integrator output returns to zero (the run-down period).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The input voltage is computed as a function of the reference voltage, the constant run-up time period, and the measured run-down time period.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The run-down time measurement is usually made in units of the converter's clock, so longer integration times allow for higher resolutions.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Likewise, the speed of the converter can be improved by sacrificing resolution.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Converters of this type (or variations on the concept) are used in most digital voltmeters for their linearity and flexibility.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This frequency is then measured by a counter and converted to an output code proportional to the analog input.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The main advantage of these converters is that it is possible to transmit frequency even in a noisy environment or in isolated form.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] However, the limitation of this circuit is that the output of the voltage-to-frequency converter depends upon an RC product whose value cannot be accurately maintained over temperature and time.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The analog part of the circuit consists of a high input impedance buffer, precision integrator and a voltage comparator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The converter first integrates the analog input signal for a fixed duration and then it integrates an internal reference voltage of opposite polarity until the integrator output is zero.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The main disadvantage of this circuit is the long duration time.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A *delta-encoded* or *counter-ramp* ADC has an up-down counter that feeds a DAC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The input signal and the DAC both go to a comparator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The circuit uses negative feedback from the comparator to adjust the counter until the DAC's output matches the input signal and number is read from the counter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Delta converters have very wide ranges and high resolution, but the conversion time is dependent on the input signal behavior, though it will always have a guaranteed worst-case.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Delta converters are often very good choices to read real-world signals as most signals from physical systems do not change abruptly.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Some converters combine the delta and successive approximation approaches; this works especially well when high-frequency components of the input signal are known to be small in magnitude.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A *pipelined ADC* (also called *subranging quantizer*) uses two or more conversion steps.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In a second step, the difference to the input signal is determined with a DAC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This difference is then converted more precisely, and the results are combined in the last step.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This can be considered a refinement of the successive-approximation ADC wherein the feedback reference signal consists of the interim conversion of a whole range of bits (for example, four bits) rather than just the next-most-significant bit.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] By combining the merits of the successive approximation and flash ADCs this type is fast, has a high resolution, and can be implemented efficiently.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A **delta-sigma ADC** (also known as a **sigma-delta ADC**) is based on a negative feedback loop with an analog filter and low resolution (often 1 bit) but high sampling rate ADC and DAC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The feedback loop continuously corrects accumulated quantization errors and performs noise shaping: quantization noise is reduced in the low frequencies of interest, but is increased in higher frequencies.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Those higher frequencies may then be removed by a downsampling digital filter, which also converts the data stream from that high sampling rate with low bit depth to a lower rate with higher bit depth.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A time-interleaved ADC uses M parallel ADCs where each ADC samples data every M:th cycle of the effective sample clock.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The result is that the sample rate is increased M times compared to what each individual ADC can manage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In practice, the individual differences between the M ADCs degrade the overall performance reducing the spurious-free dynamic range (SFDR).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] However, techniques exist to correct for these time-interleaving mismatch errors.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Longer integration times allow for higher resolutions.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The two parts of the ADC may be widely separated, with the frequency signal passed through an opto-isolator or transmitted wirelessly.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Some such ADCs use sine wave or square wave frequency modulation; others use pulse-frequency modulation.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Such ADCs were once the most popular way to show a digital display of the status of a remote analog sensor.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] A time-stretch analog-to-digital converter (TS-ADC) digitizes a very wide bandwidth analog signal, that cannot be digitized by a conventional electronic ADC, by time-stretching the signal prior to digitization.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] It commonly uses a photonic preprocessor to time-stretch the signal, which effectively slows the signal down in time and compresses its bandwidth.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] As a result, an electronic ADC, that would have been too slow to capture the original signal, can now capture this slowed-down signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] For continuous capture of the signal, the front end also divides the signal into multiple segments in addition to time-stretching.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Each segment is individually digitized by a separate electronic ADC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Finally, a digital signal processor rearranges the samples and removes any distortions added by the preprocessor to yield the binary data that is the digital representation of the original analog signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] In many cases, the most expensive part of an integrated circuit is the pins, because they make the package larger, and each pin has to be connected to the integrated circuit's silicon.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] To save pins, it is common for ADCs to send their data one bit at a time over a serial interface to the computer, with each bit coming out when a clock signal changes state.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] This saves quite a few pins on the ADC package, and in many cases, does not make the overall design any more complex.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Commercial ADCs often have several inputs that feed the same converter, usually through an analog multiplexer.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Different models of ADC may include sample and hold circuits, instrumentation amplifiers or differential inputs, where the quantity measured is the difference between two inputs.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Soundstream was probably the first digital audio recording system of commercial importance.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Analog-to-digital converters are integral to modern music reproduction technology and digital audio workstation-based sound recording.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Music may be produced on computers using an analog recording and therefore analog-to-digital converters are needed to create the pulse-code modulation (PCM) data streams that go onto compact discs and digital music files.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] The current crop of analog-to-digital converters utilized in music can sample at rates up to 192 kilohertz.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Many recording studios record in 24-bit 96 kHz pulse-code modulation (PCM) format and then downsample and dither the signal for Compact Disc Digital Audio production (44.1 kHz) or to 48 kHz for radio and television broadcast applications.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] ADCs are required in digital signal processing systems that process, store, or transport virtually any analog signal in digital form.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] TV tuner cards, for example, use fast video analog-to-digital converters.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Slow on-chip 8-, 10-, 12-, or 16-bit analog-to-digital converters are common in microcontrollers.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Digital storage oscilloscopes need very fast analog-to-digital converters, also crucial for software-defined radio and their new applications.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Digital imaging systems commonly use analog-to-digital converters for digitizing pixels.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Some radar systems use analog-to-digital converters to convert signal strength to digital values for subsequent signal processing.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Many other in situ and remote sensing systems commonly use analogous technology.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Many sensors in scientific instruments produce an analog signal; temperature, pressure, pH, light intensity etc.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] All these signals can be amplified and fed to an ADC to produce a digital representation.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Flat-panel displays are inherently digital and need an ADC to process an analog signal such as composite or VGA.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Testing an analog-to-digital converter requires an analog input source and hardware to send control signals and capture digital data output.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/analog-to-digital-converter] Some ADCs also require an accurate source of reference signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] ENOB is also used as a quality measure for other blocks such as sample-and-hold amplifiers.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] Thus, analog blocks may be included in signal-chain calculations.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] The total ENOB of a chain of blocks is usually less than the ENOB of the worst block.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] This definition compares the SINAD of an ideal converter of ENOB bits with the SINAD of the converter being tested.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] So while an ADC may use 12 bits, its ENOB may only be 9.5, corresponding to a hypothetical ideal converter with 9.5 bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] The frequency band of a signal converter where ENOB is still guaranteed is called the **effective resolution bandwidth** and is limited by dynamic quantization problems.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] For example, an ADC has some aperture uncertainty.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] The instant at which a real ADC takes a sample of its input varies from sample to sample.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] Because the input signal changes, that time variation translates to an output variation.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] For example, an ADC may sample 1 ns late.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] If the input signal is a 1 V sinewave at 1,000,000 radians/second (roughly 160 kHz), the input voltage may change by as much as 1 MV/s.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] A sampling time error of 1 ns would cause a sampling error of about 1 mV (an error in the 10th bit).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/effective-number-of-bits] If the frequency were 100 times faster (about 16 MHz), then the maximum error would be 100 times greater: about 100 mV on a 1 V signal (an error in the third or fourth bit).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] A **flash ADC** (also known as a **direct-conversion ADC**) is a type of analog-to-digital converter that uses a linear voltage ladder with a comparator at each "rung" of the ladder to compare the input voltage to successive reference voltages.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Often these reference ladders are constructed of many resistors; however, modern implementations show that capacitive voltage division is also possible.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] The output of these comparators is generally fed into a digital encoder, which converts the inputs into a binary value (the collected outputs from the comparators can be thought of as a unary value).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Flash converters are high-speed compared to many other ADCs, which usually narrow in on the correct answer over a series of stages.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Compared to these, a flash converter is also quite simple and, apart from the analog comparators, only requires logic for the final conversion to binary.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] For best accuracy, a track-and-hold circuit is often inserted in front of an ADC input.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] This is needed for many ADC types (like successive approximation ADC), but for flash ADCs, there is no real need for this because the comparators are the sampling devices.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] A flash converter requires many comparators compared to other ADCs, especially as the precision increases.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] For example, a flash converter requires $2^{n}-1$ comparators for an *n*-bit conversion.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] The size, power consumption, and cost of all those comparators make flash converters generally impractical for precisions much greater than 8 bits (255 comparators).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] In place of these comparators, most other ADCs substitute more complex logic and/or analog circuitry that can be scaled more easily for increased precision.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Flash ADCs have been implemented in many technologies, varying from silicon-based bipolar (BJT) and complementary metal–oxide FETs (CMOS) technologies to rarely used III-V technologies.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] This type of ADC is often used as a first medium-sized analog circuit verification.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] The earliest implementations consisted of a reference ladder of well-matched resistors connected to a reference voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Each tap at the resistor ladder is used for one comparator, possibly preceded by an amplification stage, and thus generates a logical 0 or 1 depending on whether the measured voltage is above or below the reference voltage of the voltage divider.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] The reason to add an amplifier is twofold: it amplifies the voltage difference.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] It, therefore, suppresses the comparator offset and the kick-back noise of the comparator towards the reference ladder is also strongly suppressed.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Typically designs from 4-bit up to 6-bit and sometimes 7-bit are produced.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Designs with power-saving capacitive reference ladders have been demonstrated.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] In addition to clocking the comparator(s), these systems also sample the reference value on the input stage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] As the sampling is done at a very high rate, the leakage of the capacitors is negligible.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Recently, offset calibration has been introduced into flash ADC designs.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Instead of high-precision analog circuits (which increase the component size to suppress variation), comparators with relatively large offset errors are measured and adjusted.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Then, a test signal is applied, and the offset of each comparator is calibrated to below the LSB value of the ADC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Another improvement to many flash ADCs is the inclusion of digital error correction.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] When the ADC is used in harsh environments or constructed from very small integrated circuit processes, there is a heightened risk that a single comparator will randomly change state resulting in a wrong code.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Bubble error correction is a digital correction mechanism that prevents a comparator that has, for example, tripped high from reporting logic high if it is surrounded by comparators that are reporting logic low.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] The number of comparators can be reduced somewhat by adding a folding circuit in front, making a so-called *folding ADC*.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Instead of using the comparators in a flash ADC only once, the folding ADC re-uses the comparators multiple times during a ramp input signal.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] If a *m*-times folding circuit is used in an *n*-bit ADC, the actual number of comparator can be reduced from $2^{n}-1$ to ${\frac {2^{n}}{m}}$ (there is always one needed to detect the range crossover).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Typical folding circuits are the Gilbert multiplier and analog wired-OR circuits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] The very high sample rate of this type of ADC enables high-frequency applications (typically in a few GHz range) like radar detection, wideband radio receivers, electronic test equipment, and optical communication links.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Moreover, the flash ADC is often embedded in a large IC containing many digital decoding functions.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Also, a small flash ADC circuit may be present inside a delta-sigma modulation loop.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/flash-adc] Flash ADCs are also used in NAND flash memory, where up to 3 bits are stored per cell as 8 voltages level on floating gates.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] An **integrating ADC** is a type of analog-to-digital converter that converts an unknown input voltage into a digital representation through the use of an integrator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In its basic implementation, the dual-slope converter, the unknown input voltage is applied to the input of the integrator and allowed to ramp for a fixed time period (the run-up period).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Converters of this type can achieve high resolution, but often do so at the expense of speed.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] For this reason, these converters are not found in audio or signal processing applications.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Their use is typically limited to digital voltmeters and other instruments requiring highly accurate measurements.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Depending on the implementation, a switch may also be present in parallel with the integrator capacitor to allow the integrator to be reset.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Inputs to the controller include a clock (used to measure time) and the output of a comparator used to detect when the integrator's output reaches zero.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The conversion takes place in two phases: the run-up phase, where the input to the integrator is the voltage to be measured, and the run-down phase, where the input to the integrator is a known reference voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] During the run-up phase, the switch selects the measured voltage as the input to the integrator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The integrator is allowed to ramp for a fixed period of time to allow a charge to build on the integrator capacitor.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] During the run-down phase, the switch selects the reference voltage as the input to the integrator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The time that it takes for the integrator's output to return to zero is measured during this phase.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In order for the reference voltage to ramp the integrator voltage down, the reference voltage needs to have a polarity opposite to that of the input voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In most cases, for positive input voltages, this means that the reference voltage will be negative.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] To handle both positive and negative input voltages, a positive and negative reference voltage is required.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The selection of which reference to use during the run-down phase would be based on the polarity of the integrator output at the end of the run-up phase.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] From the equation, one of the benefits of the dual-slope integrating ADC becomes apparent: the measurement is independent of the values of the circuit elements (R and C).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This does not mean, however, that the values of R and C are unimportant in the design of a dual-slope integrating ADC (as will be explained below).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Note that in the graph, the voltage is shown as going up during the run-up phase and down during the run-down phase.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In reality, because the integrator uses the op-amp in a negative feedback configuration, applying a positive $V_{\text{in}}$ will cause the output of the integrator to go *down*.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The *up* and *down* more accurately refer to the process of adding charge to the integrator capacitor during the run-up phase and removing charge during the run-down phase.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The resolution of the dual-slope integrating ADC is determined primarily by the length of the run-down period and by the time measurement resolution (i.e., the frequency of the controller's clock).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] During the measurement of a full-scale input, the slope of the integrator's output will be the same during the run-up and run-down phases.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This also implies that the time of the run-up period and run-down period will be equal ( $t_{u}=t_{d}$ ) and that the total measurement time will be $2t_{d}$ .
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Typically the run-up time is chosen to be a multiple of the period of the mains frequency, to suppress mains hum.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] There are limits to the maximum resolution of the dual-slope integrating ADC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] It is not possible to increase the resolution of the basic dual-slope ADC to arbitrarily high values by using longer measurement times or faster clocks.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The basic design of the dual-slope integrating ADC has a limitations in linearity, conversion speed and resolution.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] A number of modifications to the basic design have been made to overcome these to some degree.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The run-up phase of the basic dual-slope design integrates the input voltage for a fixed period of time.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] That is, it allows an unknown amount of charge to build up on the integrator's capacitor.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The run-down phase is then used to measure this unknown charge to determine the unknown voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] For a full-scale input equal to the reference voltage, half of the measurement time is spent in the run-up phase.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Reducing the amount of time spent in the run-up phase can reduce the total measurement time.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] A common implementation uses an input range twice as large as the reference voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] A simple way to reduce the run-up time is to increase the rate that charge accumulates on the integrator capacitor by reducing the size of the resistor used on the input.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This still allows the same total amount of charge accumulation, but it does so over a smaller period of time.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Note that this equation, unlike the equation for the basic dual-slope converter, has a dependence on the values of the integrator resistors.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Or, more importantly, it has a dependence on the *ratio* of the two resistance values.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This modification does nothing to improve the resolution of the converter (since it doesn't address either of the resolution limitations noted above).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The purpose of the run-up phase is to add a charge proportional to the input voltage to the integrator to be later measured during the run-down phase.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] One method to improve the resolution of the converter is to artificially increase the range of the integrating amplifier during the run-up phase.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] One method to increase the integrator capacity is by periodically adding or subtracting known quantities of charge during the run-up phase in order to keep the integrator's output within the range of the integrator amplifier.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The total accumulated charge is the charge introduced by the unknown input voltage plus the sum of the known charges that were added or subtracted.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The circuit diagram shown to the right is an example of how multi-slope run-up could be implemented.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] During the run-up the unknown input voltage, $V_{\text{in}}$ , is always applied to the integrator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Positive and negative reference voltages controlled by the two independent switches add and subtract charge as needed to keep the output of the integrator within its limits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The reference resistors, $R_{p}$ and $R_{n}$ are necessarily smaller than $R_{i}$ to ensure that the references can overcome the charge introduced by the input.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] A comparator connected to the integrator's output is used to decide which reference voltage should be applied.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This can be a relatively simple algorithm: if the integrator's output above the threshold, enable the positive reference (to cause the output to go down); if the integrator's output is below the threshold, enable the negative reference (to cause the output to go up).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The controller keeps track of how often each switch is turned on in order to account for the additional charge placed onto (or removed from) the integrator capacitor as a result of the reference voltages.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The charge added / subtracted during the multi-slope run-up form the coarse part of the result (e.g. the leading 3 digits).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] To the right is a graph of sample output from the integrator during such a multi-slope run-up.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Each dashed vertical line represents a decision point by the controller where it samples the polarity of the output and chooses to apply either the positive or negative reference voltage to the input.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] where $t_{\Delta }$ is the sampling period, $N_{p}$ is the number of periods in which the positive reference is switched in, $N_{n}$ is the number of periods in which the negative reference is switched in, and N is the total number of periods in the run-up phase.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The resolution obtained during the run-up is given by the number of periods of the run-up algorithm.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] While it is possible to continue the multi-slope run-up indefinitely, it is not possible to increase the resolution of the converter to arbitrarily high levels just by using a longer run-up time.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Error is introduced into the multi-slope run-up through the action of the switches controlling the references, cross-coupling between the switches, unintended switch charge injection, mismatches in the references, and timing errors.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Some of this error can be reduced by careful operation of the switches.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In particular, during the run-up period, each switch should be activated a constant number of times.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The algorithm explained above does not do this and just toggles switches as needed to keep the integrator output within the limits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Activating each switch a constant number of times makes the error related to switching approximately constant.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Any output offset that is a result of the switching error can be measured and then numerically subtracted from the result.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The simple, single-slope run-down is slow.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Typically, the run down time is measured in clock ticks, so to get four digit resolution, the rundown time may take as long as 10,000 clock cycles.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] A multi-slope run-down can speed the measurement up without sacrificing accuracy.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] By using 4 slope rates that are each a power of ten more gradual than the previous, four digit resolution can be achieved in roughly 40 clock ticks—a huge speed improvement.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The circuit shown to the right is an example of a multi-slope run-down circuit with four run-down slopes with each being ten times more gradual than the previous.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The switches control which slope is selected.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The switch containing $R_{d}/1000$ selects the steepest slope (i.e., will cause the integrator output to move toward zero the fastest).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] At the start of the run-down interval, the unknown input is removed from the circuit by opening the switch connected to $V_{in}$ and closing the $R_{d}/1000$ switch.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Once the integrator's output reaches zero (and the run-down time measured), the $R_{d}/1000$ switch is opened and the next slope is selected by closing the $R_{d}/100$ switch.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This repeats until the final slope of $R_{d}$ has reached zero.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The combination of the run-down times for each of the slopes determines the value of the unknown input.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In essence, each slope adds one digit of resolution to the result.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The multi-slope run-down is often used in combination with a multi-slope run-up.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The multi-slope run-up allows for a relatively small capacitor at the integrator and thus a relatively steep slope to start with and thus the option to actually use much more gradual slopes.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] It is possible to use a multi-slope rundown also with a simple run-up (like in the dual-slope ADC), but limited by the already relatively small slope for the initial phase and not much room for much smaller slopes.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In the example circuit, the slope resistors differ by a factor of 10.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This value, known as the *base* ( B ), can be any value.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] As explained below, the choice of the base affects the speed of the converter and determines the number of slopes needed to achieve the desired resolution.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The basis of this design is the assumption that there will always be overshoot when trying to find the zero crossing at the end of a run-down interval.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This will be true due to the periodic sampling of the comparator based on the converter's clock.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] To overcome this overshoot, the next slope would require no more than B clock cycles, which helps to place a bound on the total time of the run-down.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The time for the first-run down (using the steepest slope) is dependent on the unknown input (i.e., the amount of charge placed on the integrator capacitor during the run-up phase).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] where $T_{\text{first}}$ is the maximum number of clock periods for the first slope, $V_{\text{max}}$ is the maximum integrator voltage at the start of the run-down phase, and $R_{s1}$ is the resistor used for the first slope.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Converting the measured time intervals during the multi-slope run-down into a measured voltage is similar to the charge-balancing method used in the multi-slope run-up enhancement.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Each slope adds or subtracts known amounts of charge to/from the integrator capacitor.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The run-up will have added some unknown amount of charge to the integrator.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Then, during the run-down, the first slope subtracts a large amount of charge, the second slope adds a smaller amount of charge, etc. with each subsequent slope moving a smaller amount in the opposite direction of the previous slope with the goal of reaching closer and closer to zero.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] $T_{\text{slope}}$ is necessarily an integer and will ideally be less than or equal to B for the second and subsequent slopes.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] That is, B possible values with the largest equal to the first slope's smallest step, or one (base 10) digit of resolution per slope.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Which, when evaluated, shows that the minimum run-down time can be achieved using a base of e.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This base may be difficult to use both in terms of complexity in the calculation of the result and of finding an appropriate resistor network, so a base of 2 or 4 would be more common.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] When using run-up enhancements like the multi-slope run-up, where a portion of the converter's resolution is resolved during the run-up phase, it is possible to eliminate the run-down phase altogether by using a second type of analog-to-digital converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] At the end of the run-up phase of a multi-slope run-up conversion, there will still be an unknown amount of charge remaining on the integrator's capacitor.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Instead of using a traditional run-down phase to determine this unknown charge, the unknown voltage can be converted directly by a second converter and combined with the result from the run-up phase to determine the unknown input voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This equation represents the theoretical calculation of the input voltage assuming ideal components.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Since the equation depends on nearly all of the circuit's parameters, any variances in reference currents, the integrator capacitor, or other values will introduce errors in the result.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] A calibration factor is typically included in the $CV_{out}$ term to account for measured errors (or, as described in the referenced patent, to convert the residue ADC's output into the units of the run-up counters).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Instead of being used to eliminate the run-down phase completely, the residue ADC can also be used to make the run-down phase more accurate than would otherwise be possible.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] With a traditional run-down phase, the run-down time measurement period ends with the integrator output crossing through zero volts.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] There is a certain amount of error involved in detecting the zero crossing using a comparator (one of the short-comings of the basic dual-slope design as explained above).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] By using the residue ADC to rapidly sample the integrator output (synchronized with the converter controller's clock, for example), a voltage reading can be taken both immediately before and immediately after the zero crossing (as measured with a comparator).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] By combining some of these enhancements to the basic dual-slope design (namely multi-slope run-up and the residue ADC), it is possible to construct an integrating analog-to-digital converter that is capable of operating continuously without the need for a run-down interval.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Conceptually, the multi-slope run-up algorithm is allowed to operate continuously.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] To start a conversion, two things happen simultaneously: the residue ADC is used to measure the approximate charge currently on the integrator capacitor and the counters monitoring the multi-slope run-up are reset.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] At the end of a conversion period, another residue ADC reading is taken and the values of the multi-slope run-up counters are noted.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Such a continuously-integrating converter is very similar to a delta-sigma analog-to-digital converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In most variants of the dual-slope integrating converter, the converter's performance is dependent on one or more of the circuit parameters.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In the case of the basic design, the output of the converter is in terms of the reference voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In more advanced designs, there are also dependencies on one or more resistors used in the circuit or on the integrator capacitor being used.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In all cases, even using expensive precision components there may be other effects that are not accounted for in the general dual-slope equations (dielectric effect on the capacitor or frequency or temperature dependencies on any of the components).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Any of these variations result in error in the output of the converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In the best case, this is simply gain and/or offset error.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] In the worst case, nonlinearity or nonmonotonicity could result.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Some calibration can be performed internal to the converter (i.e., not requiring any special external input).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This type of calibration would be performed every time the converter is turned on, periodically while the converter is running, or only when a special calibration mode is entered.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Another type of calibration requires external inputs of known quantities (e.g., voltage standards or precision resistance references) and would typically be performed infrequently (every year for equipment used in normal conditions, more often when being used in metrology applications).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Of these types of error, offset error is the simplest to correct (assuming that there is a constant offset over the entire range of the converter).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] This is often done internal to the converter itself by periodically taking measurements of the ground potential.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Ideally, measuring the ground should always result in a zero output.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Any non-zero output indicates the offset error in the converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] That is, if the measurement of ground resulted in an output of 0.001 volts, one can assume that all measurements will be offset by the same amount and can subtract 0.001 from all subsequent results.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] Gain error can similarly be measured and corrected internally (again assuming that there is a constant gain error over the entire output range).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] The voltage reference (or some voltage derived directly from the reference) can be used as the input to the converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] If the assumption is made that the voltage reference is accurate (to within the tolerances of the converter) or that the voltage reference has been externally calibrated against a voltage standard, any error in the measurement would be a gain error in the converter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/integrating-adc] If, for example, the measurement of a converter's 5 volt reference resulted in an output of 5.3 volts (after accounting for any offset error), a gain multiplier of 0.94 (5 / 5.3) can be applied to any subsequent measurement results.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] A **successive-approximation ADC** (or **SAR ADC**) is a type of analog-to-digital converter (ADC) that digitizes each sample from a continuous analog waveform using a binary search through all possible quantization levels.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The SAR ADC was first used for experimental pulse-code modulation (PCM) by Bell Labs in the 1940s.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] In 1954, Bernard Gordon introduced the first commercial vacuum tube SAR ADC, converting 50,000 11-bit samples per second.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Drummer and Ray described the algorithm as applied to a digital voltmeter.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] This paper predates ADC integrated circuits but describes the binary search decision-making.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] An analog voltage comparator that compares *V*in to the output of a digital-to-analog converter (DAC).
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] A successive-approximation register that is updated by the results of the comparator to provide the DAC with a digital code whose accuracy increases with each successive iteration.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] A DAC that supplies the comparator with an analog voltage relative to the reference voltage *V*ref (which corresponds to the full-scale range of the ADC) and proportional to the digital code of the SAR.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The successive-approximation register is initialized with 1 in the most significant bit (MSB) and zeroes in the lower bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The register's code is fed into the DAC, which provides an analog equivalent of its digital code (initially ⁠1/2⁠*V*ref) to the comparator for comparison with the sampled input voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] If this analog voltage exceeds *V*in, then the comparator causes the SAR to reset this bit; otherwise, the bit is left as 1.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Then the next bit is set to 1, and the same test is done, continuing this binary search until every bit in the SAR has been tested.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The resulting code is the digital approximated output of the sampled input voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The algorithm's objective for the *n*th iteration is to approximately digitize the input voltage to an accuracy of 1⁄2*n* relative to the reference voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] To show this mathematically, the normalized input voltage is represented as *x* in [−1, 1] by letting *V*in = *xV*ref.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] When implemented as a real analog circuit, circuit inaccuracies and noise may cause the binary search algorithm to incorrectly remove values it believes *V*in cannot be, so a successive-approximation ADC might not output the closest value.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] It is very important for the DAC to accurately produce all 2*n* analog values for comparison against the unknown *V*in in order to produce a best match estimate.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The maximal error can easily exceed several LSBs, especially as the error between the actual and ideal 2*n* becomes large.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Manufacturers may characterize the accuracy using an effective number of bits (ENOB) smaller than the actual number of output bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] As of 2001, the component-matching limitations of the DAC generally limited the linearity to about 12 bits in practical designs and mandated some form of trimming or calibration to achieve the necessary linearity for more than 12 bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] And since kT/C noise is inversely proportional to capacitance, low noise demands a large input capacitance (which costs chip area and requires a more powerful drive buffer), which has motivated proposals around noise cancellation.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] For comparison, for a *V*ref of 5 V, the least significant bit of a 16-bit converter corresponds to 76 μV, which is around the 64 μVrms noise of a 1 pF (large for on-chip) capacitor at room temperature.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] As of 2012, SAR ADCs are limited to 18 bits, while delta-sigma ADCs (which can be 24 bits) are better suited if more than 16 bits are needed.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Calibration of the element weights allows for greater accuracy, but generally, some redundancy is then required.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] When the analog input is being compared to the internal DAC output, it effectively is being compared to each of these binary weights, starting with the 2.5 V and either keeping it or clearing it as a result.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Then by adding the next weight to the previous result, comparing again, and repeating until all the bits and their weights have been compared to the input, the result, a binary number representing the analog input, is found.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] In the nth clock cycle, if voltage is higher than digital equivalent voltage of the number in register, the (n+1)th digit from the left is set to 1.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] If the voltage were lower than digital equivalent voltage, then nth digit from left is set to zero and the next digit is set to 1.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] To perform a conversion, an N-bit ADC requires N such clock cycles, excluding the initial state.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Setup where output values of the ADC are arranged in a grid, with the vertical axis corresponding to voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] It is a 4-bit ADC that measures input voltages from 0V to 15V.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Previously established setup where an input voltage of 10.4V is provided.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Previously established setup where an input voltage of 9.4V is provided.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The successive-approximation ADC can be alternatively explained by first uniformly assigning each digital output to corresponding ranges, as shown.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] It can be seen that the algorithm essentially divides the voltage range into two regions and checks which of the two regions the input voltage belongs to.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Successive steps involve taking the identified region from before and further dividing the region into two, and continuing identification.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] This occurs until all possible choices of digital representations are exhausted, leaving behind an identified region that corresponds to only one of the digital representations.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] One of the earliest descriptions of this approach using only MOS transistors is "A capacitive charge redistribution A/D converter" .
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] This uses a charge-scaling DAC consisting of an array of individually-switched capacitors sized in powers of two and an additional duplicate of the smallest capacitor, for a total of *N*+1 capacitors for *N* bits.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Thus if the largest capacitance is *C*, then the array's total capacitance is 2*C*.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The switched capacitor array acts as both the sample-and-hold element and the DAC.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Sampling: The capacitors are switched to the input signal *V*in.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] After a brief sampling period, the capacitors will hold a charge equal to their respective capacitance times *V*in (and minus the offset voltage upon each of them), so the array holds a total charge of 2*C*·*V*in.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Hold: The capacitors are then switched to ground.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] This provides the comparator's negative input with a voltage of −*V*in.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Comparison: The comparator's output determines the bit's value for to the current test capacitor.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] In the first iteration, if *V*in is greater than *V*ref⁄2, then the comparator will output a digital 1 and otherwise output a digital 0.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Update Switch: A digital 1 result will leave the current test capacitor connected to *V*ref for subsequent iterations, while a digital 0 result will switch the capacitor back to ground.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] Thus, each *i*th iteration may or may not add *V*ref⁄2*i* to the comparator's negative input voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] For instance, the voltage at the end of the first iteration will be −*V*in + MSB·*V*ref⁄2.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] End Of Conversion: After all capacitors are tested in the same manner, the comparator's negative input voltage will have converged as close as possible (given the resolution of the DAC) to the comparator's offset voltage.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] For any high-accuracy (10 bits or greater), the capacitors must be calibrated.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The CS5015 from Crystal Semiconductor was self-calibrated on power-up.
[src:analog-to-digital-conversion/successive-approximation-adc] The patent describes the invention and calibration techniques.
